posts.title: Suhaib Sawalha
posts.content:
In my first-ever post, I want to take you on a ride through my four-year journey in Collegiate Programming Contests (CPC). It all began back in 2020 when I, along with Nicola A and Salma D, participated at PCPC and we were still high school students, so we were kind of unofficial participants. We managed to snag the 6th place out of all the teams.
Fast forward to 2021, and we're back in the PCPC, with Nicola A and Ruba Katout. Yep, you guessed it still unofficial. But this time, we clinched the 1st place among all participants! That victory punched our ticket to the ACPC-teens.
The ACPC-teens adventure took us to Luxor, Egypt, where Nicola A and I landed in 3rd place, complete with a Silver Medal.
Then came 2022, the year I started my bachelor's degree at Birzeit University. I teamed up with Basil Hijaz and Mohammad Milhem for the PCPC, and we nailed the top spot among all participants. This victory catapulted us into the ACPC once more, and this time it was held in Sharm El Sheikh, Egypt, where we held our ground, coming in 11th place and adding a Bronze Medal to our collection. But here's the kicker we also qualified for the International Collegiate Programming Contest (ICPC), making history as the first Palestinian team to achieve that milestone.
And here we are in the present, 2023. In this year's PCPC we got 1st place (3rd in a row).
It's been an incredible journey, filled with ups, downs, and lots of coding challenges. I'm excited to continue this amazing journey as the greatest is yet to come!

posts.title: orphan
posts.content:
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

int main () {

#ifndef ONLINE_JUDGE
freopen("Satoru","r",stdin);
#endif

ios_base::sync_with_stdio(false);
cin.tie(NULL);

int tt;
cin >> tt;
while (tt--) {
int n;
string s;
cin >> n >> s;
int f[26] = {}, ans = 0;
for (char c : s) {
ans += ++f[c - 'A'] == c - 'A' + 1;
}
cout << ans << "\n";
}

return 0;
}
